The paper deals with the flip graph of triangulations of a finite point set, which is a fundamental object in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the properties of the point sets that allow for an isometric embedding of the flip graph into a hypercube, which involves combinatorial and graph-theoretic arguments, making cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.GT (Graph Theory) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also mentions the efficient computation of flip distance, which involves algorithmic and data structure aspects, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the geometric properties of the point sets, such as the absence of empty convex pentagons, which involves geometric and topological arguments, making cs.SI (Symplectic Geometry) a possible sub-category.
